A girl who suffers from hearing and speech disorders reacts to the camera at a rehabilitation centre supported by Bhopal Medical Appeal, for children who were born with mental and physical disabilities, in Bhopal November 11, 2014. Have you heard of Slender Man? What started as an Internet meme and the source of a range of "fan fiction" turned almost deadly in Wisconsin, as two 12-year-old girls in have been accused of stabbing their friend 19 times because they believed the Slender Man told them to. Slender Man has similarities to other myths and legends like the Boogeyman or the Paramalfait, with the apparent power to invade dreams. Following the stabbing, the two girls allegedly left the injured youngster left lying in the woods. She had to crawl to a road where a cyclist found her lying on a pavement. Bitcoins aren't for everyone. 
"It's hard to get people to understand," says Jim Harper, an information policy expert at the libertarian Cato Institute hired by the Bitcoin Foundation to oversee its global government relations effort in Washington. Brown v. Board of Education is "still being decided every single day," Michelle Obama told high school graduates in Topeka, Kansas, this week. The case, which was combined with others that challenged segregation in schools in other parts of the country, was decided by the Supreme Court in 1954. Its 60th anniversary prompted the first lady to remind the graduates in Topeka that while the court's ruling was a major victory in the battle against bias, it was by no means the final one. ""The truth is that Brown versus Board of Ed isn't just about our history," she said, "it's about our future.": http://yhoo.it/1gyFbYa

PHOTOS: He was a prolific visual artist, but his designs of the fearsome creatures in the "Alien" and "Prometheus" films ensure the unique style of Swiss artist H.R. Giger will live on. Giger died in Gruyeres, western Switzerland, today from injuries he sustained in a fall. He was 74. The "Alien" visual biology won him an Oscar, but he also designed furniture; Ibanez issued a Giger-designed guitar, and the band Korn has been known to use a Giger-designed microphone stand in concerts. Giger suffered from insomnia and night terrors. He said his designs derived directly from his nightmares.

Five months after Minneapolis retailer Target Inc. announced a massive data breach in which the personal information of some 40 million customers was accessed, the company's CEO, president and chairman Gregg Steinhafel announced he is leaving.
Chief Financial Officer John Mulligan has been appointed interim president and CEO. Roxanne S. Austin, a member of Target's board, has been named as interim non-executive chair of the board. Both will serve in those roles until permanent replacements are named.
The departure suggests the company is trying to start with a clean slate as it wrestles with the fallout from hackers' theft of credit and debit card information on tens of millions of customers. The company's sales, profit and stock price have all suffered since the breach was disclosed.

http://yhoo.it/1j2g3YX

An "unimaginable tragedy" was prevented, say police in Waseca, Minn., after arresting a 17-year-old high school student and accusing him of plotting to kill his family, then set off pressure-cooker bombs in his school cafeteria.

William Evans, a veteran of 45 marathons, has run the Boston Marathon 18 times. He finished the 2013 Boston Marathon in 3 hours and 34 minutes, qualifying him for this year's running. 
But don't expect to see him running the event this year.
Evans, who in January became Boston police commissioner, will instead focus on security around the event. 
He's promised a "soft approach" with what are expected to be record crowds: no metal detectors, no long security lines, no stopping spectators from enjoying the race. 
Instead, Evans urges common sense, with uniformed and plainclothes officers — twice as many as last year—on alert for "strange" behavior and ordered to politely "shoo away" spectators near the finish line if it gets too crowded.
Still, he will run that day—just well before the race starts.
"Oh yeah, I'll be up at 4:30. …I'll get my run in," Evans said.

In Papua, New Guinea, an island nation of 6 million people in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, reliable statistics are hard to find on domestic violence. The most recent survey is more than than 20 years old, and showed about half of women on the island reported being raped. Anecdotal evidence suggests little has changed: More than two thirds of women now report being subjected to domestic violence. One study of a rural area showed almost all women reported being raped. In addition, traditional beliefs about sorcery often lead villagers, confronted with a death or unexpected misfortune, to accuse a woman of witchcraft. Photographer Vlad Sokhin's new exhibit on the island's extreme domestic violence, "Crying Meri," attracted immediate international attention and prompted the launch of a Kickstarter campaign to publish the photos. Pictured is Rasta, accused of sorcery in her village during a funeral, then beaten and strangled before she escaped with the loss of her hand.
http://yhoo.it/1bJRb6i

PHOTOS: Dr. Erin Kimmerle of the University of Florida holds in her hand a pants button found in an exhumed grave at the Arthur G. Dozier reform school for boys in Marianna, Florida. Kimmerle led a team of researchers to unearth remains of two children from the grounds, and plans to exhume 50 graves. The state-run reform school opened in 1900 and closed in 2011 for budget reasons, though allegations of rape, torture, beating and murder of child inmates were nearly constant through its history. Child remains will be examined and DNA-tested to try to determine who was buried there and why they died. Formerly called the Florida School for Boys, it was once the largest juvenile reform institute in the United States, intended for 13 to 21-year-olds, though the two bodies found are thought to be as young as 10. The school has had a long and disgraceful history; Dr. Kimmerle said she became interested in the investigation because no records were kept of who died and were buried there, highly unusual for a state institution.

PHOTOS: An air of mystery surrounds sacred Buddhist tattoos, or Sak Yant. Those who get them believe they have magical properties, such as protecting their bearers from bullets, or jealous lovers. Soldiers get them to protect themselves from wounds in battle. Gamblers and gangsters get them to improve their business dealings or luck. Others receive the tattoo -- done by sharp knitting-needle sized spikes dipped in magical ink, one hammered point at a time -- to help make a life transition. The script is in ancient Khmer, or Khom, and is made up of prayers and often, the signature of the artist, a Buddhist monk or trained practitioner. Photographer David Longstreath recorded one of the more famous sacred tattoo festivals in the world at the Wat Bang Phra temple in Thailand, and tells the story of what he saw. Westerners, such as Angelina Jolie and jazz singer Melody Gardot, are wearers of sacred Buddhist tattoos, though the Thai government has recently considered banning tourists from getting them, because they are not meant to be worn as fashion statements.

Has technology taken over your life? It did for author and comedian Baratunde Thurston. The constant digital presence of the self-proclaimed "social media guy," caused Thurston to hit a point of mental exhaustion.

"What I realized first was how much time I spent trying to think of things to say. Like, what is the caption for this moment of my life?" Thurston told ABC's Katie Couric. It was then that he decided to step back from his digital persona for 25 days and take a digital vacation.

Constantly being tuned into the alternate digital universe can create a false sense of urgency and dominate your mental freedom, which Thurston believes can be the most inhibiting factor in a digital addiction.

"It's harder to create a great work, if you are constantly reacting to everything in your life. And without hours and days and weeks of relatively unscheduled disconnected things, you don't give your mind time to process and develop some next big thing," Thurston said.

So, are you ready to unplug? How would you survive without your smartphone, email and a constant digital connection to the world? http://yhoo.it/11TGJEl

Chris Hondros and Joseph Duo were the unlikeliest of friends. One was a veteran war photographer and the other a Liberian soldier who had dropped out of school in the 10th grade to go to war. Their lives couldn't have been more different, save for a fleeting moment in July 2003 when an iconic image tied them together forever. 

The image of Duo frozen in midair, drunk in the glory of war, became not only an iconic reminder of the deadly conflict in Liberia, but one of the most important images in modern war photography and a finalist for the 2004 Pulitzer Prize.

The story behind that photograph—and the subsequent friendship between Hondros and Duo—is the backbone of a documentary journalist Greg Campbell hopes to make about Hondros. Campbell, the author of "Blood Diamonds" and Hondros' best friend, launched a Kickstarter campaign this week to fund "Hondros: A Life in Frames," which will explore the photographer's life by telling the stories behind some of his most famous photos.

What's a derecho storm? Well, if you live on the Eastern Seaboard, one may be heading for you right now. The National Weather Service has issued storm warnings for most of the mid-Atlantic U.S., as concerns that the damaging winds, large hail and flash floods the storm has already left in its wake move east. The storm didn't quite go derecho as expected this morning, but meteorologists report the patterns that could form such a storm could be seen by satellite. The term, a Spanish word meaning "straight ahead," or "direct," was coined in 1888. Derecho storms are characterized by their large size and a shape like a comma or a bow, along with strong winds. A derecho last year caused at least $1 billion in damage from Chicago to Washington, killing 13 and leaving 4 million without power as a result of near-100 mph winds. Pictured is lighting caused by the storm over Chicago.
